<section id="the-pricing-architecture-of-access" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Pricing Architecture of Access</h2>
  <p>The non-opioid analgesics market is projected to reach $14.5 billion by 2030. That number is not a measure of how many patients will be helped. It is a measure of how much revenue the pharmaceutical industry expects to extract from a market it has identified as underserved. Those two things are related, but they are not the same thing, and conflating them is how access failures get laundered as market successes.</p>
  <p>Suzetrigine launched at a list price of approximately $15.50 per tablet, with a typical acute pain course running to several hundred dollars — a price point that is not catastrophic in isolation but becomes significant when mapped against the demographics of opioid crisis impact. The communities most devastated by opioid overdose deaths — rural, lower-income, predominantly uninsured or underinsured — are precisely the communities where out-of-pocket drug costs function as effective barriers to access. Opioids, by contrast, are largely generic, cheap, and covered by virtually every formulary. A 30-day supply of generic oxycodone costs under $30 at most pharmacies.</p>
  <p>Opioid overdose deaths exceeded 80,000 in the United States in 2023, with prescription opioids implicated in a substantial proportion of those deaths. Chronic pain affects approximately 50 million Americans and costs the economy over $635 billion annually in healthcare expenditure and lost productivity. These are the populations and the economic contexts into which suzetrigine is being introduced at a price point calibrated for commercially insured patients in urban health systems. The math is not complicated. The pattern is not new.</p>
  <p>Insurance formulary placement will determine whether suzetrigine reaches the patients who need it most, or whether it becomes a premium option for patients who were never at serious opioid risk in the first place. Early formulary decisions have been mixed. Some major payers have placed suzetrigine on preferred tiers with manageable copays. Others have implemented prior authorization requirements that create administrative friction sufficient to push prescribers back toward opioids — which require no prior authorization because they are cheap and established. The system's incentive architecture, in other words, continues to favor the drug that kills people over the drug that doesn't, because the drug that kills people is already paid for.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-surveillance-gap-that-remains" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Surveillance Gap That Remains</h2>
  <p>Novel mechanisms mean unknown long-term profiles. This is not a rhetorical hedge — it is a pharmacological reality that the anti-NGF experience illustrates concretely. Nav1.8 is expressed predominantly in peripheral nociceptors, but "predominantly" is not "exclusively." There are Nav1.8-expressing neurons in the enteric nervous system, which governs gut motility. There are questions about Nav1.8's role in cardiac ischemic preconditioning that have not been fully resolved in human populations. The selectivity of suzetrigine for Nav1.8 over other sodium channel subtypes is high by pharmacological standards — but high selectivity in a Phase 3 trial population of surgical patients over weeks is a different claim than high selectivity in a population of chronic pain patients over years.</p>
  <p>Post-market surveillance in the United States operates through the FDA's MedWatch system and, for drugs with specific safety concerns, through Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS). Neither mechanism is particularly good at detecting low-frequency adverse events in real time. The opioid crisis itself is partly a post-market surveillance failure — the addiction and overdose signal was present in the data for years before regulatory action matched the scale of the problem. There is no structural reason to assume the surveillance infrastructure has been meaningfully reformed in the interim.</p>
  <p>This is not an argument against suzetrigine's approval. The acute pain data is strong, the mechanistic rationale is sound, and the risk-benefit calculation for a drug that produces no respiratory depression or abuse potential signals is favorable compared to opioids in the approved indication. It is an argument for treating the post-market period as the beginning of the safety story, not the end of it — and for building surveillance infrastructure proportionate to the scale of deployment being anticipated in a $14.5 billion market.</p>
</section>

