<section id="closing-the-gap-opening-another" class="reveal">
  <h2>Closing the Gap, Opening Another</h2>
  <p>The science gap is real and it is closing. Nav1.8 selectivity is a genuine mechanistic achievement. The Phase 3 data for suzetrigine is not manufactured enthusiasm — it is a controlled trial in a peer-reviewed journal showing that analgesia can be decoupled from addiction circuitry in human patients. The anti-NGF effect sizes in chronic musculoskeletal pain, despite the RPOA signal, represent a meaningful advance over the NSAID ceiling that has constrained chronic pain management for decades. The ENT1 and combination pathway data, while earlier-stage, suggest the mechanistic diversity needed to eventually address the heterogeneity of chronic pain presentations. These are real scientific developments, and dismissing them as pharma hype would be as intellectually dishonest as uncritically amplifying them.</p>
  <p>But the knowledge failure that made opioids inevitable was embedded in a system that also had regulatory failures, commercial failures, and access failures — and that system has not been replaced. It has been patched. The FDA that approved suzetrigine is the same FDA whose post-market surveillance missed the opioid addiction signal at scale. The insurance market that will determine suzetrigine's reach is the same market that covers generic oxycodone without prior authorization. The healthcare infrastructure that will prescribe these drugs is the same infrastructure that, in rural and low-income communities, is already stretched beyond capacity to manage the opioid crisis it helped create.</p>
  <p>The patients most likely to benefit from non-opioid alternatives are the same patients least likely to afford them at launch pricing. This is not a coincidence produced by oversight or market inefficiency. It is a structural feature of a pharmaceutical development system that prices drugs according to what commercially insured urban patients can bear, in a country where the populations bearing the greatest burden of opioid harm are disproportionately rural, poor, and underinsured. The science gap closed. The equity gap did not. And if the history of American pharmaceutical access is any guide, it will not close on its own.</p>
</section>

